Question: Flatten a list of sentences into a list of unique words.
Input:
List<String> sentences = Arrays.asList("hello world", "hello java");

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams flatten sentences into unique words using flatMap + split + distinct. For input ["hello world", "hello java"], returns ["hello", "world", "java"].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream sentences → flatMap(sentence -> Arrays.stream(sentence.split("\\s+"))) → distinct() → collect(toList()).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class FlattenUniqueWords {
    public static List<String> flattenUniqueWords(List<String> sentences) {
        return sentences.stream()
                       .flatMap(sentence -> Arrays.stream(sentence.split("\\s+")))
                       .distinct()
                       .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> sentences = Arrays.asList("hello world", "hello java");
        List<String> words = flattenUniqueWords(sentences);
        System.out.println(words);  // [hello, world, java]
    }
}

#Thought Process
flatMap essential: split("\\s+") → array → Arrays.stream → flattens nested streams. \\s+ handles multiple spaces. distinct() removes "hello" duplicate. Preserves first-occurrence order.
​

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty outer list: [].
Empty sentences: Skipped (empty stream).
Multiple spaces: \\s+ collapses.
Null sentences: NPE on split.
Trailing spaces: Empty strings filtered by distinct? No—distinct("") keeps if present.
